Diagnosis.
Female of 

Labena madoricola

can be distinguished from all other females of New World species by the following characters in combination: mesopleuron centrally smooth and shiny; metapleuron entirely smooth and shiny, without longitudinal striae; propodeum with lateral end of posterior transverse carina not raised into rounded flange (
Figs 1C–D
); area spiracularis open externally (
Fig. 1C
); area lateralis large, closed by a strong pleural carina, its surface greater than area coxalis, with abscissa of lateral carina bordering it internally, joining posterior transverse carina dorsally of centre of area coxalis (
Fig. 1C
); area superomedia hexagonal broaded centrally, strongly delineated anteriorly, posteriorly weaker and tending to be semicircular, very large, 1.1 × as broad as long (
Fig. 1D
); anterior transverse carina of propodeum joining area superomedia at centre (
Fig. 1D
); fore wing with a black spot at distal 0.3 of marginal cell and distal 0.7 of submarginal cell (
Fig. 2D
); areolet transverse, 0.63 × as broad as length of distal abscissa of 
M
; vein 2 
m-cu
joining to areolet at mid part (
Fig. 2D
); mid tibia at distal 0.7 strongly inflated, with about five-seven conspicuous flattened bristles on outer surface; ovipositor slightly upcurved (
Fig. 2B
), sheaths 1.54 × the length of the hind tibia (
Fig. 3C
); flagellum in dorsal view entirely black or blackish brown (
Fig. 3C
); head orange without a transverse jet-black mark in front of occipital carina (
Fig. 3D
); hind leg and metasoma entirely orange (
Figs 3
C-D).

